b'$COUP hurting here https://t.co/dHugcFe6ez'

b'-- While it remains to be seen whether $COUP with a $28B market cap can become the $CRM ($203B market cap) of business spend management, the company currently has a lot going for it, but will still have to continue to deliver strong results going forward.'

b'-- $COUP has a large growth runway as management estimates a TAM of $56B.\n\n-- Trading at a P/S ratio of 40x, $COUP has a premium valuation. But sales have been growing, expenses have been decreasing, and free cash flow is being generated. https://t.co/SG3nNoL2SZ'

b"-- In addition, $COUP may benefit from high switching costs. Business spend management software can take months to integrate, especially for large enterprises. \n\n-- The investment in (and efficacy of) $COUP's software may make customers think twice about switching."

b'-- $COUP platform enables a flywheel that creates a network effect. More customers means more spend with suppliers, which in turn provides $COUP\'s users with "community intelligence" to optimize spend. https://t.co/2nkZFh8Eyo'
b"-- Industry analysts have repeatedly recognized $COUP's platform as industry leading. https://t.co/UCKuw3pz6h"

b"-- $COUP's customer base of ~1,400 businesses speaks to the efficacy of its product offerings. Its customers include Walmart, Toyota, Salesforce, Lululemon, BMW, Zendesk, Aon, and Barclays. https://t.co/7hIl6CS6hr"

b'-- $COUP has advantages over incumbents like $ORCL and $SAP in that its software was built ground up to run on the cloud.\n\n-- In contrast, the decades-old incumbents have been slow to transition from on premise offerings to cloud native offerings.'

b"-- These are essential functions for businesses whether they purchase raw materials or ink pens. But purchases often occur in silos with one segment in the dark as to another segment's purchasing.\n\n-- $COUP offers a single pane of glass to manage spend across an enterprise."

b"-- $COUP's cloud native software enables companies to track, manage, and analyze their spending.\n\n-- What's this mean? Among other things: managing invoices and payments, reconciling spend with budgets, tracking discounts and rebates, and ensuring purchases comply with policy. https://t.co/IKZ01JknlU"

b"-- Founded in 2006 by former Oracle executives Noah Eisner and Dave Stephens, $COUP aims to become the Salesforce of business spend management.\n\n-- Eisner and Stephens helped build Oracle's procurement platform. Believing they could do better, they left to start $COUP."

b'Spotlight: $COUP (+133% YTD)

-- Businesses that sell products to other businesses (B2B) have been among the top performing stocks in recent years. 

-- Yet these stocks can go overlooked because consumers lack firsthand exposure to their offerings. $COUP may be one such stock. https://t.co/KIRISdUVIs'
